{"id":13996,"date":"2023-02-23T23:32:09","date_gmt":"2023-02-23T23:32:09","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/www.kidzcompanion.com\/?page_id=13996"},"modified":"2023-10-20T14:59:02","modified_gmt":"2023-10-20T14:59:02","slug":"diagnosis","status":"publish","type":"page","link":"https:\/\/www.kidzcompanion.com\/diagnosis\/","title":{"rendered":"Diagnosis"},"content":{"rendered":"<p>[vc_row full_width=&#8221;stretch_row_content_no_spaces&#8221; equal_height=&#8221;yes&#8221; css=&#8221;.vc_custom_1697296041725{margin-right: 80px !important;margin-left: 80px !important;}&#8221;][vc_column width=&#8221;1\/2&#8243; css=&#8221;.vc_custom_1697296077864{background-color: #91bf38 !important;}&#8221;][vc_column_text css_animation=&#8221;none&#8221; css=&#8221;.vc_custom_1697663464685{padding-right: 80px !important;padding-bottom: 25px !important;padding-left: 60px !important;}&#8221;]<span style=\"color: #ffffff;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family: Antonio; font-size: 40px;\">Diagnosis.<\/span><\/strong><\/span><\/p>\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 18px; color: #ffffff;\">Detecting Autism Spectrum Disorder (ASD) at an early stage can have a profound impact on the life of a child or young adult with ASD, potentially minimizing the challenges associated with the disorder and enabling the child to flourish.<\/span><\/p>\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 18px; font-family: 'Barlow Semi Condensed'; color: #ffffff;\">Parents should not hesitate to address any concerns they might have regarding their child&#8217;s behavior or development\u2014the way he or she plays, learns, speaks, and act with their pediatrician or health caregiver.<\/span>[\/vc_column_text][\/vc_column][vc_column width=&#8221;1\/2&#8243; css=&#8221;.vc_custom_1677195628999{background-image: url(https:\/\/www.kidzcompanion.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/02\/ASD-1.png?id=14000) !important;background-position: center !important;background-repeat: no-repeat !important;background-size: cover !important;}&#8221;][\/vc_column][\/vc_row][vc_row full_width=&#8221;stretch_row_content&#8221; css=&#8221;.vc_custom_1697663516995{padding-top: 40px !important;padding-right: 80px !important;padding-left: 0px !important;}&#8221;][vc_column][vc_row_inner gap=&#8221;20&#8243; css=&#8221;.vc_custom_1677198531929{margin-top: -25px !important;margin-left: 100px !important;}&#8221;][vc_column_inner width=&#8221;4\/5&#8243;][vc_column_text css=&#8221;.vc_custom_1697813773319{padding-right: 80px !important;padding-left: 80px !important;}&#8221;]<span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"color: #404040;\">Diagnosing autism spectrum disorder (ASD) can be difficult because there is no medical test, like a blood test, to diagnose the disorder. Doctors <\/span>rely on observing the behaviors of very young children and listening to the concerns of their parents. He or she <span style=\"color: #404040;\">look at the child&#8217;s developmental history and behavior to make a diagnosis. ASD can sometimes be detected at 18 months of age or younger.<\/span><\/span><\/p>\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 16px; color: #404040;\"><strong>Early diagnosis requires a collaboration between parents and pediatricians.<\/strong> Parents should feel comfortable bringing up any concerns with their child\u2019s development\u2014the way he or she plays, learns, speaks, and acts. <img decoding=\"async\" class=\"wp-image-16955 alignright\" src=\"https:\/\/www.kidzcompanion.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/10\/Family-with-kid-visiting-pediatrician-flat-vector-illustration.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"321\" height=\"229\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.kidzcompanion.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/10\/Family-with-kid-visiting-pediatrician-flat-vector-illustration.png 3679w, https:\/\/www.kidzcompanion.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/10\/Family-with-kid-visiting-pediatrician-flat-vector-illustration-300x214.png 300w, https:\/\/www.kidzcompanion.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/10\/Family-with-kid-visiting-pediatrician-flat-vector-illustration-1024x731.png 1024w, https:\/\/www.kidzcompanion.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/10\/Family-with-kid-visiting-pediatrician-flat-vector-illustration-768x549.png 768w, https:\/\/www.kidzcompanion.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/10\/Family-with-kid-visiting-pediatrician-flat-vector-illustration-1536x1097.png 1536w, https:\/\/www.kidzcompanion.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/10\/Family-with-kid-visiting-pediatrician-flat-vector-illustration-2048x1463.png 2048w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 321px) 100vw, 321px\" \/><\/span><\/p>\n<ul>\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 16px; color: #404040;\">Over the past decade, many pediatricians screen for autism during well-child checkups. As a result, those exhibiting early signs of ASD are receiving referrals for appropriate assessment.<\/span><\/li>\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 16px; color: #404040;\">ASD can sometimes be detected at 18 months or younger.\u00a0Some children show ASD symptoms within the first 12 months. In others, symptoms may not show up until 24 months+.<\/span><\/li>\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 16px; color: #404040;\">Some children with ASD gain new skills and meet\u00a0developmental milestones, until around 18-24 months of age and then they may stop gaining new skills or lose the skills they once had.<\/span><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n<p>[\/vc_column_text][vc_column_text css=&#8221;.vc_custom_1693536316624{margin-right: 30px !important;padding-right: 40px !important;padding-left: 80px !important;}&#8221;]<\/p>\n<div class=\"wpb_text_column wpb_content_element vc_custom_1674083268867\">\n<div class=\"wpb_wrapper\">\n<p><strong><span style=\"font-size: 40px; font-family: Antonio;\"><span style=\"color: #333333;\">Early Diagnosis Is Critical<\/span><span style=\"color: #f27822;\">.<\/span><\/span><\/strong><\/p>\n<\/div>\n<\/div>\n<p>[\/vc_column_text][vc_column_text css=&#8221;.vc_custom_1697813623067{padding-right: 80px !important;padding-left: 80px !important;}&#8221;]<\/p>\n<div class=\"wpb_text_column wpb_content_element vc_custom_1674151677813\">\n<div class=\"wpb_wrapper\">\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 16px; color: #404040;\">An autism diagnosis begins as part of a child\u2019s regular well visits, which should be made in conjunction with your child\u2019s pediatrician. The pediatrician may ask specific questions or complete a questionnaire about the child\u2019s development.\u00a0 The pediatrician will likely ask you a series of questions,\u00a0including:<\/span><\/p>\n<ul>\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 16px; color: #404040;\">Does your child act in a way that is unusual for his or her age? Does your child seem less social or interact with other children and adults less?<\/span><\/li>\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 16px; color: #404040;\">Does your child fail to make eye contact with you or others?<\/span><\/li>\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 16px; color: #404040;\">Does your child exhibit any sensitivities to light, sound, or touch?<\/span><\/li>\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 16px; color: #404040;\">Does your child fail to respond to efforts to capture his or her attention?<\/span><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 16px; color: #404040;\">Furthermore, you and your pediatrician should be keeping an eye out for developmental milestones. These include:<\/span><\/p>\n<ul>\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 16px; color: #404040;\">By six months, has your child smiled?<\/span><\/li>\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 16px; color: #404040;\">By nine months, has your child begun to copy facial expressions that you make or mimic sounds?<\/span><\/li>\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 16px; color: #404040;\">At a year old, has your child started to babble and coo?<\/span><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n<\/div>\n<\/div>\n<div class=\"vc_separator wpb_content_element vc_separator_align_center vc_sep_width_60 vc_sep_border_width_3 vc_sep_pos_align_center vc_separator_no_text vc_sep_color_grey vc_custom_1674150735915 vc_custom_1674150735915\"><\/div>\n<p>[\/vc_column_text]\t<div class=\"evc-button-wrapper evc-btn-center\">\n<a class=\"evc-button evc-shortcode  evc-btn-solid evc-btn-large \" href=\"https:\/\/www.kidzcompanion.com\/development-milestones-%e2%94%82-early-childhood\/\" title=\"Development Milestones \u2502 Early Childhood\" style=\"font-family: mulish;font-size: 16px;background-color: #f3781e\" data-hover-background-color=\"#b0a285\">\n\t\t<span class=\"evc-btn-text\">Development Milestones \u2502 Early Childhood<\/span>\n<\/a>\n\t<\/div>\n[\/vc_column_inner][vc_column_inner width=&#8221;1\/5&#8243; css=&#8221;.vc_custom_1697296584198{margin-left: 100px !important;padding-left: 120px !important;}&#8221;][vc_column_text css=&#8221;.vc_custom_1697812642063{padding-top: 20px !important;padding-right: 20px !important;padding-bottom: 20px !important;padding-left: 20px !important;background-color: #f0ead8 !important;}&#8221;]<span style=\"font-size: 14px; color: #404040;\">Autism is one of the more prevalent disorders with which children are currently diagnosed. According to the statistics, 1 in 36 children born in the United States is now diagnosed with autism.\u00a0<\/span><\/p>\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 14px; color: #404040;\">With diagnoses on the rise, more parents are experiencing the challenges that come with raising a child with difficulty in communicating, interacting socially, or controlling repetitive behaviors.<\/span>[\/vc_column_text][vc_column_text css=&#8221;.vc_custom_1697812670831{padding-top: 20px !important;padding-right: 20px !important;padding-bottom: 20px !important;padding-left: 20px !important;background-color: #f0ead8 !important;}&#8221;]<span style=\"font-size: 14px;\">Autism screening is usually administered by a pediatrician during a routine checkup. However, diagnosing ASD can be difficult because there is no objective clinical test for the disorder. Instead, doctors must rely on the child\u2019s development and behavior history and careful observations of certain behaviors.<\/span>[\/vc_column_text][vc_column_text css=&#8221;.vc_custom_1697296500543{padding-top: 20px !important;padding-right: 20px !important;padding-bottom: 20px !important;padding-left: 20px !important;background-color: #f0ead8 !important;}&#8221;]<span style=\"font-size: 14px; font-family: 'Barlow Semi Condensed';\">The importance of a diagnosis cannot be understated. For obvious reasons, a child cannot receive treatment unless they have been formally diagnosed with autism as early intervention is necessary to improve a child\u2019s cognitive skills, social interactions, and brain development.\u00a0<\/span>[\/vc_column_text][vc_column_text css=&#8221;.vc_custom_1697296510951{padding-top: 20px !important;padding-right: 20px !important;padding-bottom: 20px !important;padding-left: 20px !important;background-color: #f0ead8 !important;}&#8221;]<span style=\"font-size: 14px;\">The doctor may observe the child or ask questions about his or her behavior at home and while interacting with other children on the playground.<\/span>[\/vc_column_text][vc_column_text css=&#8221;.vc_custom_1697296521083{padding-top: 20px !important;padding-right: 20px !important;padding-bottom: 20px !important;padding-left: 20px !important;background-color: #f0ead8 !important;}&#8221;]<\/p>\n<div class=\"wpb_text_column wpb_content_element \">\n<div class=\"wpb_wrapper\">\n<p><span style=\"color: #63666a; font-size: 14px; font-family: 'Barlow Semi Condensed';\">The purpose of an autism screening is to identify common early signs of autism. The following are early signs of autism, however, they do not necessarily need to be present.<\/span><\/p>\n<\/div>\n<\/div>\n<div class=\"wpb_text_column wpb_content_element \">\n<div class=\"wpb_wrapper\">\n<ul>\n<li><span style=\"color: #63666a; font-size: 14px; font-family: 'Barlow Semi Condensed';\">Delays in communicating with others including speech and gestures\u00a0<\/span><\/li>\n<li><span style=\"color: #63666a; font-size: 14px; font-family: 'Barlow Semi Condensed';\">Not responding to one\u2019s own name<\/span><\/li>\n<li><span style=\"color: #63666a; font-size: 14px; font-family: 'Barlow Semi Condensed';\">Getting upset over minor changes in routine<\/span><\/li>\n<li><span style=\"color: #63666a; font-size: 14px; font-family: 'Barlow Semi Condensed';\">Avoiding many, if not most, forms of physical contact<\/span><\/li>\n<li><span style=\"color: #63666a; font-size: 14px; font-family: 'Barlow Semi Condensed';\">Showing little interest in objects or people.<\/span><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n<\/div>\n<\/div>\n<p>[\/vc_column_text][\/vc_column_inner][\/vc_row_inner][vc_row_inner gap=&#8221;20&#8243; css=&#8221;.vc_custom_1677198531929{margin-top: -25px !important;margin-left: 100px !important;}&#8221;][vc_column_inner width=&#8221;4\/5&#8243;]\t<div class=\"evc-button-wrapper evc-btn-center\">\n<a class=\"evc-button evc-shortcode  evc-btn-solid evc-btn-large \" href=\"https:\/\/www.kidzcompanion.com\/early-signs-of-autism-spectrum-disorder-2\/\" title=\"Early Signs of Autism Spectrum Disorder\" style=\"font-family: mulish;font-size: 14px;color: #ffffff;background-color: #f3781e\" data-hover-color=\"#ffffff\" data-hover-background-color=\"#808b91\">\n\t\t<span class=\"evc-btn-text\">Early Signs of ASD<\/span>\n<\/a>\n\t<\/div>\n[vc_column_text css=&#8221;.vc_custom_1693536506992{padding-top: 60px !important;padding-right: 80px !important;padding-left: 80px !important;}&#8221;]<\/p>\n<div class=\"wpb_text_column wpb_content_element vc_custom_1674151677813\">\n<div class=\"wpb_wrapper\">\n<p><strong><span style=\"font-family: Anton; font-size: 24pt; color: #63666a;\"><span style=\"font-family: Antonio; color: #333333;\"><span style=\"font-size: 40px;\">CDC<\/span> &amp; <span style=\"font-size: 40px;\">Diagnosis of Autism Spectrum Disorder<\/span><\/span><span style=\"color: #f27822;\">.<\/span><\/span><\/strong><\/p>\n<p><span style=\"font-family: 'Barlow Semi Condensed'; font-size: 14pt; color: #404040;\">The Centers for Disease Control (CDC) has developed screening tools that can help parents, family members, and doctors determine if an autism diagnosis has been made. The CDC specifically recommends that children be checked for all developmental delays at nine, 18, and 30 months. The CDC also recommends that specific ASD screenings take place at both 18 and 24 months.<\/span><\/p>\n<p><span style=\"font-family: 'Barlow Semi Condensed'; font-size: 14pt; color: #404040;\">Once a diagnosis is suspected, the child will be referred to a specialist. That specialist \u2013 or a team of specialists \u2013 will perform multiple tests and evaluations. The team may vary, but according to the National Institute of Mental Health, it will likely include the following:<\/span><\/p>\n<ul>\n<li><span style=\"font-family: 'Barlow Semi Condensed'; font-size: 14pt; color: #404040;\">Developmental pediatrician<\/span><\/li>\n<li><span style=\"font-family: 'Barlow Semi Condensed'; font-size: 14pt; color: #404040;\">A child psychologist or psychiatrist with experience in behavior and brain development<\/span><\/li>\n<li><span style=\"font-family: 'Barlow Semi Condensed'; font-size: 14pt; color: #404040;\">A neuropsychologist<\/span><\/li>\n<li><span style=\"font-family: 'Barlow Semi Condensed'; font-size: 14pt; color: #404040;\">A speech-language pathologist<\/span><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n<p><span style=\"font-family: 'Barlow Semi Condensed'; font-size: 14pt; color: #404040;\">Children suspected of having autism will be given a variety of tests. They will also be evaluated for their language abilities, cognitive development, and age-appropriate skills. Other tests, like hearing tests and blood work, may also be necessary. From there, a specialist will give a formal diagnosis and make treatment recommendations.<\/span><\/p>\n<\/div>\n<\/div>\n<p>[\/vc_column_text][vc_column_text css=&#8221;.vc_custom_1693536535939{margin-right: 30px !important;padding-right: 40px !important;padding-left: 80px !important;}&#8221;]<span style=\"font-family: Antonio; font-size: 40px; color: #63666a;\"><span style=\"color: #333333;\">Autism &amp; Young Adults<\/span><span style=\"color: #f27822;\">.<\/span><\/span>[\/vc_column_text][vc_column_text css=&#8221;.vc_custom_1693537533276{margin-right: 30px !important;padding-right: 40px !important;padding-left: 80px !important;}&#8221;]<span style=\"font-size: 14pt; color: #404040;\">While awareness about autism has dramatically increased in children, there are young adults\u00a0that might\u2019ve been overlooked for any number of reasons. While an\u00a0autism diagnosis may not be quite as impactful for a young adult as it is for a child, it is still vitally important as young adults can find real\u00a0benefits to being diagnosed with autism.<\/span><\/p>\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 14pt; color: #404040;\">The signs of autism in a young adult are slightly different than those that you may see in a child, as developmental delays are no longer relevant for diagnosis purposes.<img decoding=\"async\" class=\"wp-image-14573 alignright\" src=\"https:\/\/www.kidzcompanion.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/08\/Home-Page-Child-3.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"260\" height=\"262\" \/><\/span><\/p>\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 14pt; color: #404040;\">Indeed, many of these symptoms are specifically related to social situations and emotional intelligence. These signs often include:<\/span><\/p>\n<ul>\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 14pt; color: #404040;\">Problems with understanding, reading, and reacting to social hints and cues<\/span><\/li>\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 14pt; color: #404040;\">Difficulty socializing<\/span><\/li>\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 14pt; color: #404040;\">Difficulty maintaining close, personal relationships<\/span><\/li>\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 14pt; color: #404040;\">Difficulty expressing emotion and a flat affect when it comes to interpersonal communication<\/span><\/li>\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 14pt; color: #404040;\">Repetitive behaviors<\/span><\/li>\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 14pt; color: #404040;\">Difficulty adapting to changes in routines<\/span><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n<p>[\/vc_column_text][\/vc_column_inner][vc_column_inner width=&#8221;1\/5&#8243; css=&#8221;.vc_custom_1697296584198{margin-left: 100px !important;padding-left: 120px !important;}&#8221;][\/vc_column_inner][\/vc_row_inner][\/vc_column][\/vc_row][vc_row full_width=&#8221;stretch_row_content&#8221; css=&#8221;.vc_custom_1693538391997{padding-top: 20px !important;padding-bottom: 40px !important;}&#8221;][vc_column width=&#8221;1\/4&#8243;][\/vc_column][vc_column width=&#8221;1\/2&#8243;]\t<div class=\"evc-button-wrapper evc-btn-center\">\n<a class=\"evc-button evc-shortcode  evc-btn-solid evc-btn-large \" href=\"https:\/\/www.kidzcompanion.com\/aba-assessment\/\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"font-family: mulish;font-size: 14px;color: #ffffff;background-color: #f3781e\" data-hover-color=\"#ffffff\" data-hover-background-color=\"#808b91\">\n\t\t<span class=\"evc-btn-text\">Learn More About ABA Assessment<\/span>\n<\/a>\n\t<\/div>\n[vc_empty_space][\/vc_column][vc_column width=&#8221;1\/4&#8243;][\/vc_column][\/vc_row]<\/p>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>[vc_row full_width=&#8221;stretch_row_content_no_spaces&#8221; equal_height=&#8221;yes&#8221; css=&#8221;.vc_custom_1697296041725{margin-right: 80px !important;margin-left: 80px !important;}&#8221;][vc_column width=&#8221;1\/2&#8243; css=&#8221;.vc_custom_1697296077864{background-color: #91bf38 !important;}&#8221;][vc_column_text css_animation=&#8221;none&#8221; css=&#8221;.vc_custom_1697663464685{padding-right: 80px !important;padding-bottom: 25px !important;padding-left: 60px !important;}&#8221;]Diagnosis. Detecting Autism Spectrum Disorder (ASD) at an early stage can have a profound impact on the life of a child or young adult with ASD, potentially minimizing the challenges associated with the disorder and enabling [&hellip;]<\/p>\n","protected":false},"author":1,"featured_media":0,"parent":0,"menu_order":0,"comment_status":"closed","ping_status"